    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDef_3">• Irrational numbers have nonterminating, nonrepeating decimals (e.g., √2 = 1.414... ).\n
• Every positive irrational has a negative counterpart.\n
• Equal irrationals share identical decimal digits.\n
• Examples: √2, π, and most logarithms or trigonometric values.</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefQuestion_3">Is √2 a rational number? (True / False)</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerOne_3">True</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerTwo_3">False</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerThree_3">Neither</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_3">False</string>

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryProperties_3">• Irrationals come from roots of non-perfect powers.\n
• They can\'t be written as fractions.\n
• Comparison is done digit by digit.\n
• π and √3 are classic examples.</string>
