    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDef_3">• Real Numbers: include all rationals and irrationals.\n
• Arithmetic laws (commutative, associative, distributive) apply to them.\n
• Irrationals + rationals may yield rational or irrational results.\n
• Arithmetical nth root: for a ≥ 0, there\'s one non-negative b such that bⁿ = a.\n
• Coordinates: any point (x, y) lies in the plane; distance |M₁M₂| = √((x₂−x₁)² + (y₂−y₁)²).</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefQuestion_3">What is the distance between points (0, 0) and (3, 4)?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerOne_3">7</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerTwo_3">5</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerThree_3">√7</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_3">5</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryProperties_3">Properties of Real Numbers:\n
• The sum or product of two rationals is always rational.\n
• The sum of a rational and an irrational is always irrational.\n
• The product of a nonzero rational and an irrational is always irrational.\n
• The product of two irrationals can be rational (e.g., √2 · √2 = 2) or irrational.\n
• Real numbers are ordered: for any a, b, exactly one holds: a &lt; b, a = b, or a &gt; b.</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsQuestion_3">Is the sum of a rational and an irrational number always irrational? (True / False)</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerOne_3">True</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_3">False</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_3">True</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExamples_3">Find the distance between M₁(1, 2) and M₂(4, 6).\n
Step 1: Apply the formula: d = √((4−1)² + (6−2)²).\n
Step 2: d = √(3² + 4²) = √(9 + 16) = √25.\n
Step 3: d = 5.</string>
