    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDef_3">• Arithmetical nth root: ⁿ√a = b if bⁿ = a (a ≥ 0).\n
• Rules:\n
1. ⁿ√a = ⁿᵏ√aᵏ\n
2. ⁿ√a·ⁿ√b = ⁿ√(ab)\n
3. ⁿ√a/ⁿ√b = ⁿ√(a/b)\n
4. (ⁿ√a)ᵐ = ⁿ√aᵐ\n
5. ᵐ√ⁿ√a = ᵐⁿ√a.\n
• Like roots: simplifiable only when indices and radicands match.\n
• Key identity: ⁿ√aⁿ = |a| if n even; = a if n odd.</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDefQuestion_3">What is ³√8?</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDefAnswerOne_3">4</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDefAnswerTwo_3">3</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDefAnswerThree_3">2</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_3">2</string>

    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryProperties_3">Further Root Properties:\n
• Roots with the same index can be multiplied or divided under one radical sign.\n
• A root of a root ᵐ√ⁿ√a equals ᵐⁿ√a (multiply the indices).\n
• To compare roots with different indices, convert them to a common index.\n
• Rationalizing a denominator removes the root from the bottom: 1/√a = √a/a.\n
• ⁿ√aⁿ = |a| for even n (always non-negative), and = a for odd n.</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryPropsQuestion_3">What is √√16?</string>
